user@localhost ~ $ rchar --help
usage: rchar [-h] [-c [CHARSCOPE] | -C | -P | -E | -A] [-v] [--version]
             [length]

A handy tool to generate (pseudo-)random ASCII strings.

positional arguments:
  length                The quantity of characters to generate in string.

optional arguments:
  -h, --help            show this help message and exit
  -c [CHARSCOPE], --charscope [CHARSCOPE]
                        A pseudo-random string generated by this charscope.
  -C, --ctrl33          A pseudo-random string generated from the 33 ASCII
                        control characters.
  -P, --print95         A pseudo-random string generated from the 95 standard
                        ASCII characters (default=True).
  -E, --extprint223     A pseudo-random string generated from the 223
                        standard+extended ASCII characters.
  -A, --full256         A pseudo-random string generated from all 256 ASCII
                        characters.
  -v, --verbose         Display rchar.py debug output during runtime.
  --version             show program's version number and exit
user@localhost ~ $ rchar 7
g?zdY%7
user@localhost ~ $ rchar -E 7
?<D????
user@localhost ~ $ rchar -c abcd 7 | hexdump -C
00000000  64 63 61 63 61 61 62 0a                           |dcacaab.|
00000008
user@localhost ~ $ rchar -C 7 | hexdump -C
00000000  15 15 02 11 0e 1b 19 0a                           |........|
00000008
user@localhost ~ $ for i in {1..3}; do id=`rchar 4`; echo "New file: $id"; \
> touch $id; done
New file: @d*L
New file: `K?p
New file: V6T,
